The '''Ford Insomnia Response to Stress Test''' is a diagnostic tool used to identify individuals predisposed to [[insomnia]]. It is a nine-item self-report instrument that tests the likelihood that an individual will get sleep disturbances following various stressful events.<ref name="MyUser_Ncbi.nlm.nih.gov_July_16_2015c">{{cite journal |title=Stress-related sleep disturbance and polysomnographic response to caffeine |pmc=2535762 | pmid=16996309 |doi=10.1016/j.sleep.2006.03.019 |volume=7 |year=2006 |journal=Sleep Med. |pages=567–72 | last1 = Drake | first1 = CL | last2 = Jefferson | first2 = C | last3 = Roehrs | first3 = T | last4 = Roth | first4 = T}}</ref><ref name="NLM2">{{cite journal |title=Vulnerability to Insomnia: The Role of Familial Aggregation  |pmc=2358982 | pmid=17825612 |doi=10.1016/j.sleep.2007.04.012 |volume=9 |year=2008 |journal=Sleep Med. |pages=297–302 | last1 = Drake | first1 = CL | last2 = Scofield | first2 = H | last3 = Roth | first3 = T}}</ref>

