{{for|the American business executive and speaker|Joel G. Block}}
{{notability|Biographies|date=May 2018}}
'''Joel Block''' (born 1943) is a [[psychologist]] and author on relationships and sexuality.<ref>New York Times article: https://www.nytimes.com/1997/03/09/nyregion/a-look-at-a-corporate-feud-that-undermined-an-ad-empire.html?scp=7&sq=joel%20block%20psychologist&st=cse</ref>  Block is an assistant clinical professor of psychiatry at [[Hofstra Northwell School of Medicine]]. He is also a senior psychologist at [[Northwell Health]], where he was the training supervisor of the hospital's Sexuality Center for twenty years, until 2002.

==Early life and education==
Block was born in 1943 in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and later attended the [[State University of New York]], where he obtained a [[Bachelor of Science]] in Education/Psychology. He obtained a Master of Science degree in [[psychology]], and later went on to obtain his [[doctorate]] in psychology from [[Syracuse University]]. He also undertook a one year postdoctoral fellowship in Cognitive Behavioral Therapy from the [[Albert Ellis]] Institute.

==Author==
Block's books include:

*''The Other Man, The Other Woman: Understanding and Coping with Extramarital Affairs'', Grosset & Dunlap, 1978{{ISBN|0-448-14568-5}}
*''To Marry Again'', Grosset & Dunlap, 1979 {{ISBN|0-448-16420-5}}
*''Friendship'', Macmillan, 1983
*''Secrets of Better Sex'', Parker/Simon & Schuster, 1996, {{ISBN|0-7352-0283-4}}
