'''Patients Know Best''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[social enterprise]], with an aim of putting patients in control of their own medical records.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/magazine/archive/2011/03/start/power-to-the-patient |title=How 'Patients Know Best' is putting your health back into your hands (Wired UK) |publisher=Wired.co.uk |date=2012-08-30 |accessdate=2012-09-09}}</ref> Patients Know Best also integrates into the [[National Health Service|NHS]] [[Connecting for Health]] network to provide patients with tools to work with clinicians. Its Chairman is Dr [[Richard Smith (editor)]]. Mohammad Al-Ubaydli is the founder and chief executive officer.
The system has been trialled in the [[United States|US]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ehi.co.uk/news/ehi/7704/patients-know-best-in-us-trial |title=E-Health Insider :: Patients Know Best in US trial |publisher=Ehi.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2012-09-09}}</ref> It is in use in 19 different languages at more than 60 hospitals throughout the UK, Australia, Ireland, Germany, Hong Kong, the USA and the Netherlands.
After trials conducted by [[Abertawe Bro Morgannwg University Health Board]] it is to be rolled out across Wales in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Patient-centred online medical records get the green light in Wales|url=http://www.pharmaceutical-journal.com/20203075.article|accessdate=17 July 2017|publisher=Pharmaceutical Journal|date=29 June 2017}}</ref>
